[{"id":42965,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d656fb63-2538-409b-95de-cf2e0afaeb5b-9896742.PNG\" style=\"width: 322px; height: 188px;\" /></p><p>As per sign conventions, object distance&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>u</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>, focal length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>.</p><p>From the mirror formula</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>u</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>45</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>900</mn></mrow><mn>25</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>And&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>u</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>u</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>35</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>700</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>140</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Now,&nbsp;length of image<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>36</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>140</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>108</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>140</mn></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>32</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43005,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ddfd22b7-ddfd-40ed-a4e6-ae918c7d393f-1.jpg\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 175px;\" /></p><p>For convex lenses, let radius of curvature is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math>. Then,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Now for concave lens,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>c</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>R</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>30</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>f</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>30</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>f</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42973,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a602dd3b-e6cd-486c-a0f1-5b8ab6f42b4a-9894770_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 337px; height: 160px;\" /></p><p>Given here: Focal length of convex lens,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Now, as seen in figure, image from lens is formed at point&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>, whose location is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>&nbsp;from mirror. Thus,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>&nbsp;from lens.</p><p>Using lens equation, we have</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Putting the value,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>u</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Thus, object is placed at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>&nbsp;from lens.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42951,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>120</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>110</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>140</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>130</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>&nbsp;It is given that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ad1d98e6-33a8-4285-b74e-098fb9f797e7.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 343px;\" /></p><p>The formula for angle of deviation is&nbsp;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi></math></p><p>Substituting the values,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>120</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43016,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>cos</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msqrt></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>cos</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mi>min</mi></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfrac><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>cos</mi><mfrac><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>cos</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42949,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let&#39;s assume that the original position of the bubble is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;from one side of the ice cube of side&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>.</p><p>When the bubble is seen from one side, it can be written that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>For the view from the other side, it can be written that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>From equations (1) and (2), it is given that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mn>24</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn><mi>&#956;</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>4</mn><mi>&#956;</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>24</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42988,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/593cece8-f6aa-4032-9c67-397c58632c75-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 175px;\" /></p><p>When the refracted light just grazes the boundary&nbsp;the incident&nbsp;angle is called a critical angle.</p><p>Using snell&#39;s law at face <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mi>C</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>sin</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>sin</mi><mn>90</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43007,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mfrac><mi>f</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mfrac><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","Very high, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8734;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#8734;</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>u</mi></mfrac></math><br />Put <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math><br />Magnification <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42931,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false"],"answer":2,"solution":"As $\\lambda_{\\text {red }}>\\lambda_{\\text {yellow }}>\\lambda_{\\text {violet }}$\nLight ray with longer wavelength bends less.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42904,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5L9gzDtxNqLAEbw69lMB8_2vpZAAIT9LtoxRb9Ni3M8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7eL5gOubVl-hwkpKM-rUER8x6ZRZH22wQCiqA6kR2ok.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/njJbQvSbSqhYLhBWdlFKg9NcR7ieh0M3Xj4ruXrpzlM.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/l2PDBjUjKljwkuUfpnJ-Cal6NXVFjRt4N7cUtdo7MP4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"$(u+f)(v-f)=f^2$\n\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Jx9A3h9sk7KWGyiltecVu0lQTOuHewnaKvgm4L8g1Ho.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43071,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#956;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>&#956;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br />When joined together<br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">q</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43127,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$45^{\\circ}$","$60^{\\circ}$","$75^{\\circ}$","$30^{\\circ}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Normal to the plane is $z$-axis\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\cos \\theta_1=\\frac{A_z}{A}=\\frac{10}{20}=\\frac{1}{2}, \\theta_1=60 \\\\\n& \\mu_1 \\sin \\theta_1=\\mu_2 \\sin \\theta_2 \\Rightarrow \\sqrt{2} \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}=\\sqrt{3} \\sin \\theta_2 \\Rightarrow \\theta_2=45^{\\circ}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":42867,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$30^{\\circ}$","$15^{\\circ}$","$45^{\\circ}$","$60^{\\circ}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Let the refractive index of the prism be $n_1 = n$ and the refractive index of the coating on the exit surface be $n_2 = \\frac{n}{2}$.<br>At the condition of minimum deviation, the angle of refraction at the first surface $r_1$ and the angle of incidence at the second surface $r_2$ are equal, i.e., $r_1 = r_2 = \\frac{A}{2}$, where $A$ is the prism angle.<br>The problem states that at the exit surface, the light meets the condition of critical angle. Therefore, $r_2 = \\theta_c$.<br>The critical angle $\\theta_c$ for the interface between the prism and the coating is given by $\\sin \\theta_c = \\frac{n_2}{n_1}$.<br>Substituting the values, $\\sin \\theta_c = \\frac{n/2}{n} = \\frac{1}{2}$.<br>Thus, $\\theta_c = 30^\\circ$.<br>Since $r_2 = \\theta_c$, we have $r_2 = 30^\\circ$.<br>Using the relation $r_1 = r_2 = \\frac{A}{2}$ for minimum deviation, we get $\\frac{A}{2} = 30^\\circ$.<br>Therefore, $A = 60^\\circ$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42974,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/681a207b-9ffa-48f1-84b2-db7a7f58c5bd-9894213.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 289px;\" /></p><p>Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi></math>&nbsp;be the critical angle.</p><p>Then,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sinC</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></math>,&nbsp;where, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi></math> is the refractive index of glass.</p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sinC</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p>As the angle of incidence is equal to the critical angle, so using Snell&#39;s law,</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sinC</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></msqrt><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p>Now, lateral displacement of the ray is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sec</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>r</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi>sin</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfenced><mi>sec</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>26</mn><mo>)</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42985,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula for deviation due to a thin prism is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p><p>Therefore, for prism&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p>And for prism&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>55</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mi>net</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#176;</mo></msup></math></p><p>Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42884,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$\\tan ^{-1}(4 / 3)$","$\\tan ^{-1}(3 / 4)$","$\\sin ^{-1}(3 / 4)$","$\\cos ^{-1}(3 / 4)$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fEM6rHy6r1itCRQnV-3RCZCR8n1SsnKYRAM9ZsQWp9w.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{r}+\\theta_{\\mathrm{C}}=90^{\\circ} \\\\ & \\mu_1 \\sin \\theta=\\mu_2 \\sin \\mathrm{r} \\\\ & \\sin \\theta=\\frac{\\mu_2}{\\mu_1} \\sin \\left(90-\\theta_{\\mathrm{C}}\\right) \\\\ & \\sin \\theta=\\frac{\\mu_2}{\\mu_1} \\cos \\theta_{\\mathrm{C}} \\\\ & \\sin \\theta_{\\mathrm{C}}=\\frac{\\mu_1}{\\mu_2}\\end{aligned}$<br/>$\\begin{aligned} & \\sin \\theta=\\frac{\\mu_2}{\\mu_1} \\sqrt{1-\\frac{\\mu_1^2}{\\mu_2^2}} \\\\ & \\sin \\theta=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\mu_2^2-\\mu_1^2}{\\mu_1^2}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\frac{25}{16}-1}{1}} \\\\ & \\sin \\theta=\\frac{3}{4} \\\\ & \\theta=\\sin ^{-1}\\left(\\frac{3}{4}\\right)\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43124,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$20 \\mathrm{~mm}$","$100 \\mathrm{~mm}$","$120 \\mathrm{~mm}$","$80 \\mathrm{~mm}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HQ6I77Z0kD6IeFqgoOgG42mM0w1kX6tDGQtcnHid0zI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nTo obtain final image at infinity, object which is the image formed by objective should be at focal distance of eye-piece. By lens formula (for objective)\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\frac{1}{v_0}-\\frac{1}{u_0}=\\frac{1}{f_0} \\\\\n\\text { or, } \\quad & \\frac{1}{v_0}-\\frac{1}{-25}=\\frac{1}{20} \\\\\n\\Rightarrow \\quad & \\frac{1}{v_0}=\\frac{1}{20}-\\frac{1}{25}=\\frac{5-4}{100}=\\frac{1}{100} \\mathrm{~mm} \\\\\n\\therefore \\quad & v_0=100 \\mathrm{~mm}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nTherefore the distance between the lenses\n$$\n=v_0+f_e=100 \\mathrm{~mm}+20 \\mathrm{~mm}=120 \\mathrm{~mm}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":42876,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For refraction at a single spherical surface, we use the formula: $\\frac{\\mu_2}{v} - \\frac{\\mu_1}{u} = \\frac{\\mu_2 - \\mu_1}{R}$<br>Given data:<br>Refractive index of air $\\mu_1 = 1.0$<br>Refractive index of glass $\\mu_2 = 1.5$<br>Radius of curvature $R = +50$ cm (convex surface)<br>Object is at infinity for a parallel beam, so $u = -\\infty$<br>Substituting the values:<br>$\\frac{1.5}{v} - \\frac{1.0}{-\\infty} = \\frac{1.5 - 1.0}{50}$<br>$\\frac{1.5}{v} - 0 = \\frac{0.5}{50}$<br>$\\frac{1.5}{v} = \\frac{1}{100}$<br>$v = 1.5 \\times 100 = 150$ cm<br>The image is formed at a distance of $150$ cm from the pole (vertex) of the spherical surface.<br>The question asks for the distance $x$ from the centre of curvature.<br>Distance from centre of curvature $x = |v - R|$<br>$x = 150 - 50 = 100$ cm","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42873,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["between the focus $(F)$ and the centre of curvature $(C)$ of the mirror ONLY","between the pole($P$) and the focus $(F)$ of the concave mirror ONLY","beyond the centre of the curvature $(C)$ of the mirror ONLY","at any point beyond the focus $(F)$ of the mirror"],"answer":3,"solution":"In the parallax method for determining the focal length of a concave mirror, we use an object pin and its real image formed by the mirror.<br>The method of 'no parallax' involves aligning the tip of the object pin with the tip of its real image. This is only possible if the image formed is real.<br>For a concave mirror, a real image is formed only when the object is placed at any position beyond the focus ($F$), i.e., $u > f$.<br>If the object is placed between the pole ($P$) and the focus ($F$), the image formed is virtual, and it cannot be caught on a screen or used for the standard parallax alignment with a physical pin in front of the mirror.<br>Therefore, the object should be placed at any point beyond the focus ($F$) of the mirror to ensure a real image is formed.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43106,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["200","100","400","150"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given : $f_0=1.2 \\mathrm{~cm} ; f_e=3.0 \\mathrm{~cm}$ $u_0=1.25 \\mathrm{~cm} ; M_{\\infty}=$ ?\nFrom $\\frac{1}{f_0}=\\frac{1}{v_0}-\\frac{1}{u_0}$\n$$\n\\Rightarrow \\quad \\frac{1}{1.2}=\\frac{1}{v_0}-\\frac{1}{(-1.25)}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&\\Rightarrow \\quad \\frac{1}{v_0}=\\frac{1}{1.2}-\\frac{1}{1.25} \\\\\n&\\Rightarrow v_0=30 \\mathrm{~cm}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nMagnification at infinity,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&M_{\\infty}=-\\frac{v_0}{u_0} \\times \\frac{D}{f_e} \\\\\n&=\\frac{30}{1.25} \\times \\frac{25}{3} \\quad(\\because D=25 \\mathrm{~cm} \\text { least distance }\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nof distinct vision)\n$$\n=200\n$$\nHence the magnifying power of the\ncompound microscope is 200","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":43119,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a7e19c56-111b-410d-bf99-0c19c08b9b03-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 134px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/359847ae-865f-40ef-9ceb-66f5e0819665-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 131px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/55ba6bdc-884c-410a-a8e1-0abadbbcb42c-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 133px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/77743476-0862-487d-8e74-88e6e087878b-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 133px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>We know that angle of deviation depend upon the angle of incidence. If we determine experimentally the angle of deviation corresponding to different angles of incidence then and then plot <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi></math> (on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis) and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi></math> (on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>-axis), we get a curve as shown in figure.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0e4d8c2a-73dd-4fd8-baf3-0675c44f6e69-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 268px;\" /></p><p>Clearly, if angle of incidence is gradually increased from a small value, the angle of deviation first decreases, becomes minimum for a particular angle of incidence and then begins to increase.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":43076,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$90^{\\circ}$","$30^{\\circ}$","$60^{\\circ}$","$45^{\\circ}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"For minimum deviation:\r\n\r\n$\\mathrm{r}_{1}=\\mathrm{r}_{2}=\\frac{\\mathrm{A}}{2}=30^{\\circ}$\r\n\r\nby Snell's law $\\mu_{1} \\sin \\mathrm{i}=\\mu_{2} \\sin \\mathrm{r}$\r\n\r\n$1 \\times \\sin i=\\sqrt{3} \\times \\frac{1}{2}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\Rightarrow i=60$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42993,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>10</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The speed of light in a medium is inversely proportional to the refractive index of the material. Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Let the thickness is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>d</mi><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>d</mi><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>.&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42990,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Given:\r\nobject using the lens formula:\r\n\\(\\begin{aligned}& \\frac{1}{f}=\\frac{1}{v \\prime}-\\frac{1}{w^{\\prime}} \\\\\\Rightarrow & \\frac{21}{240} \\mathrm{~cm}=\\frac{3}{35} \\mathrm{~cm}-\\frac{1}{u^{\\prime}} \\\\\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{u^{\\prime}} & =\\frac{3}{35} \\mathrm{~cm}-\\frac{21}{240} \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\\\Rightarrow & \\frac{1}{u^{\\prime}}=\\frac{1}{5}\\left[\\frac{3}{7} \\mathrm{~cm}-\\frac{21}{48} \\mathrm{~cm}\\right] \\\\\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{u^{\\prime}} & =\\frac{1}{5}\\left[\\frac{144-147}{336}\\right] \\\\\\Rightarrow u^{\\prime} & =-560 \\mathrm{~cm}=-5.6 \\mathrm{~m}\\end{aligned}\\)\r\nHence, the object should be at \\(5.6 \\mathrm{~m}\\) in front of the lens.\r\nHence, the oblect should be moved by 5.6-24= \\(3.2 \\mathrm{~cm}\\).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42853,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$45$","$30$","$28$","$58$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Velocity of light in vacuum, $c = 3 \\times 10^8$ m/s<br><br>Velocity of light in the prism, $v = 2.12 \\times 10^8$ m/s<br><br>Refractive index of the prism material, $\\mu = \\dfrac{c}{v} = \\dfrac{3 \\times 10^8}{2.12 \\times 10^8} \\approx 1.414 \\approx \\sqrt{2}$<br><br>For an equilateral prism, the angle of the prism $A = 60^\\circ$.<br><br>Using the prism formula:<br><br>$\\mu = \\dfrac{\\sin\\left(\\dfrac{A + \\delta_m}{2}\\right)}{\\sin\\left(\\dfrac{A}{2}\\right)}$<br><br>$\\sqrt{2} = \\dfrac{\\sin\\left(\\dfrac{60^\\circ + \\delta_m}{2}\\right)}{\\sin(30^\\circ)}$<br><br>$\\sqrt{2} = \\dfrac{\\sin\\left(30^\\circ + \\dfrac{\\delta_m}{2}\\right)}{\\dfrac{1}{2}}$<br><br>$\\sin\\left(30^\\circ + \\dfrac{\\delta_m}{2}\\right) = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} = \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}$<br><br>$30^\\circ + \\dfrac{\\delta_m}{2} = 45^\\circ$<br><br>$\\dfrac{\\delta_m}{2} = 15^\\circ$<br><br>$\\delta_m = 30^\\circ$<br><br>Answer: $30$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43139,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$1 \\mathrm{D}$","$-1 \\mathrm{D}$","$25 \\mathrm{D}$","None of these"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{m}}}{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{air}}}=\\frac{\\left(\\frac{\\mu_{\\ell}}{\\mu_{\\mathrm{a}}}-1\\right)}{\\left(\\frac{\\mu_{\\ell}}{\\mu_{\\mathrm{m}}}-1\\right)}$\n$\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{m}}=5 / 8 \\mathrm{D}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":42940,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>45</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>45</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Given <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>So, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>15</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>For convex mirror, virtual image is formed for real object. Thus, magnification <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>m</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>The magnification can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Equation (1) implies that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>v</mi><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>u</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>The relation between the object distance, image distance and the focal length of the mirror is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>f</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Equation (2) implies that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>u</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>u</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43111,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$1.033 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$3.581 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$1.3533 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$1.90 \\mathrm{~cm}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Real depth $=5 \\mathrm{~cm}+1 \\mathrm{~cm}=6 \\mathrm{~cm}$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/vi1LONKyrZMhZRLmiPx905jEDfZ1NxZfkPxrIUZRDL8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nApparent depth $=\\frac{\\mathrm{d}_1}{\\mu_1}+\\frac{\\mathrm{d}_2}{\\mu_2}+\\ldots$\n$=\\frac{5}{1.33}+\\frac{1}{1.5}$\n$\\simeq 3.8+0.7 \\simeq 4.5 \\mathrm{~cm}$\n$\\therefore$ Shift $=6 \\mathrm{~cm}-4.5 \\mathrm{~cm} \\cong 1.5 \\mathrm{~cm}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":43067,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>305</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math> radian","<math><mn>610</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math> radian","<math><mn>152.5</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math> radian","<math><mn>457.5</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math> radian"],"answer":0,"solution":"Limit of resolution of the telescope <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.22</mn><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.22</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>500</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>200</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>305</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></math> radian","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43018,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["Angle of refraction is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>24</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.","Angle of refraction is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.","Refraction is not possible.","Angle of refraction is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>53</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>sin&#952;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mi>sin&#952;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin&#952;</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>sin&#952;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></math></p><p>Total internal reflection will happen.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null}]